Titanic

Winston Saunders

December 31, 2014

Introduction

This is a model for the kaggle Titanic dataset. The idea is to make a predictive model of survivor. Judging from leaderboards,

        training <- read.csv("train.csv", na.strings=c("NA", ""))
        testing <- read.csv("test.csv", na.strings=c("NA", ""))

First model

Base first model on Sex and Age per tutorial. Since there are many NAs in the data we replace those with the mean ages for male or females.

The model is trained with a Random Forest.

The mean male age is 30.7 years and the mean female age is 27.9 years. Here is a snapshot of the cleaned data. Note the fractional year on substituted values.

training[1:6,c("Survived", "Age", "Sex")]
##   Survived      Age    Sex
## 1        0 22.00000   male
## 2        1 38.00000 female
## 3        1 26.00000 female
## 4        1 35.00000 female
## 5        0 35.00000   male
## 6        0 30.72664   male

The first model looks at the following function

        modelfunction<-Survived~Age+Sex
## note: only 1 unique complexity parameters in default grid. Truncating the grid to 1 .

Here is the confusion table

conf$table
##           Reference
## Prediction   0   1
##          0 105   8
##          1  38  27

The accuracy is 74.2%.

Second Approach - nested feature modeling

Age data substitution appears to be a critical factor in model accuracy. Age plays a strong role in survival. Since there are a lorge number of NAs in the age data which need to be modeled, lets see if the method of directly substituting mean age can be improved.

Since Passenger class affects survival its logical to look for dependency there.

The age model is set up as follows

        agemodel<-glm(Age~Pclass+Sex, data=trainfull)

RMSE of the age-fit is 13.7 versus of using the mean 15.

Here is a plot of the fitted age versus actual age. Note some values have been substituted

The survivial model function is:

        modelfunction <- Survived~Age+Sex+Pclass
## note: only 2 unique complexity parameters in default grid. Truncating the grid to 2 .

Resulting in the following confusion matrix

##           Reference
## Prediction   0   1
##          0 172   4
##          1  41  50

The accuracy is 83.15 versus earlier 74.16%.

Model4

Segregate

        train1.m<-train1[train1$Sex=="male",]

        test1.f<-test1[test1$Sex=="female",]
        trainfull.f<-train1.f[is.na(train1.f$Age)==FALSE, ]

Based on this plot there is a substantial population of young survivors who have helpers.

        modelfunction <- Survived~AgeModel+Pclass+Sex

Attempt 4

I tried an Old Fart model (identify old men, some of whom seemed to have survived). But that did not impove accuracy.

The age model is set up as follows

        agemodel<-glm(Age~Pclass+Sex, data=trainfull)

It slightly improves the RMSE of a fit is 13.7 versus of using the mean 15. An improvement. So Il use that to fill in blanks.

Another way to look at this data is by buckets

        train1$OldFarts<- -1
        train1$OldFarts[train1$Sex=="male"&train1$Age>60] <- 1

        test1$OldFarts<- -1
        test1$OldFarts[test1$Sex=="male"&test1$Age>60] <- 1
        modelfunction <- Survived~Age+Pclass+OldFarts+Sex

Here is the confusion matrix

##           Reference
## Prediction   0   1
##          0 172   4
##          1  42  49

The accuracy is 82.77 compares to earlier 83.15%.
